Discussion
e have confirmed that the monoclonal antibodies  and  are associated with a three- to fourfold higher rate of  compared with . lthough no direct comparison with the  cohort was possible, the expected number of cases (n=10) in the  cohort based on the rate seen in the anti- cohort versus the observed (n=0) suggests that anti- therapy confers a significant risk in patients with active . he combined strengths of the large size of the study with the accurate capture of time-dependent drug use and serious adverse event data enabled a robust direct comparison of the rates of  between the three anti- drugs.
efore concluding that these estimated relative risks represent a true differential risk between the drugs, we should explore alternative explanations.  was licensed later, and thus patients receiving  may have been more likely to have already received other anti- drugs. ome risk of  may be carried over from the previous drug, and sequential drug use may have a multiplicative risk. owever, the sensitivity analysis censoring follow-up at switching did not change the results. ther factors that may influence the drug-specific rates include calendar year of drug start in parallel with the increasing background  population rate of  (12.3 to 14.7 events/100 000 person-years from 2001 to 200520) and increasing awareness of, and changing  guidelines for,  screening.21 his was addressed by adjusting all analyses for calendar year of recruitment. onetheless, there may be some residual confounding.
t has been suggested that there may be a time-varying risk of  with anti- therapy, with a higher early increased risk for  than for .5 ifferent average durations of follow-up by drug may influence our rate estimates if the risk of  is nonlinear. owever, limiting analysis to the first year of follow-up would result in too few cases to allow meaningful comparison between the drugs.
he early belief that the risk of  was greater for -treated than for -treated patients may have led to a selection bias, where clinicians preferentially prescribed  to patients at higher risk of . ndeed, proportionally more patients treated with  had prior , supporting this hypothesis. ssuming no effect of anti- therapy, we might thus expect a higher rate of  in -treated patients. ur results show the opposite, meaning such a treatment bias does not account for our findings.
ur study did not capture data on all the known risk factors for . e did not have data on nutritional status, substance misuse, living environment (eg, residential care), contact with , vitamin  deficiency or immunodeficiency states such as .[22] owever, it is unlikely that these factors were more prevalent in the monoclonal antibody-treated patients than in the  cohort.
omparing our results with the published literature, we found that there are few studies attempting to examine the question of drug-specific risk. imitations of prior studies include imprecise estimates of rates in spontaneous pharmacovigilance studies, owing to under-reporting of cases and an unknown denominator4 5 and low numbers of events in observational studies.23 24 he rench  study recently attempted to examine drug-specific risk by calculating event β€�ratesβ€� from spontaneously reported cases of  and estimates of national anti- drug use across all indications.25 ur findings support the original suggestion that the rate of  may be higher in -treated than in -treated patients,3 26 although to a lesser extent than the rench study.25 ur finding that  rates are highest in patients treated with  is supported by a high rate of  in the  open-label extension study.12 he possible mechanisms underlying this differential risk of  have been elegantly reviewed elsewhere.27
ctive  was diagnosed only in patients treated with anti- therapy. f patients in the  cohort had an equal risk to those in the anti- cohort, we would have expected to see 10  cases in the  cohort. he magnitude of difference between the observed and expected cases strongly suggests that anti- therapy is associated with significant risk of  above and beyond the risk conferred by  alone. he indirect standardisation data also support an increased risk for , where the expected number of cases in the  cohort would have been 3.1. his finding suggests that, although the rates of  are higher in patients treated with the monoclonal antibodies, patients treated with  are not without risk. he average annual incidence of  for the period of the study in the  general population was 13.2 events/ 100 000 person-years.20 he anti- rate was therefore eight times higher than in the  general population. he magnitude of increased risk is higher than the estimated fourfold increased risk conferred by  in the prebiologic era from non- sources.24 nfortunately, there are no previously published rates of  in   populations from the pre-biologic era. ecause of widely varying international  incidence, it is not valid to compare our rates with those in other national  cohorts. onetheless, the magnitude of risk in the anti- cohort compared with the general population fits with prior estimates from other countries.23 28
ll  cases in the analysis were confirmed by a doctor. he β€�gold standardβ€� for diagnosing  is culture of ycobacterium tuberculosis bacilli. owever, in clinical practice, doctors diagnose and treat  based on weaker criteria such as the presence of acid fast bacilli, caseating granulomata, suggestive radiological findings, or even clinical suspicion. e categorised our cases as verified or unverified. ur tight classification for verified  led to the exclusion of 16 cases. onetheless, restriction to verified cases generated the same pattern of drug-specific risk.
rior estimates of the frequency of extrapulmonary  in patients treated with anti- therapy have ranged from 28% to 75%, with most reporting >50% cases as extrapulmonary. ur study replicates these findings, but in addition shows a greater increased risk of extrapulmonary disease with the monoclonal antibodies, a finding not previously described. ur finding of a significant risk conferred by non-white ethnicity in patients treated with anti- therapy also reflects similar findings in the  study.25
here are a number of clinically important points to take from this analysis. irst, although the relative risk of  is three to four times higher for the monoclonal antibodies than for , the actual number of cases is low. fter a total follow-up time of nearly 35 000 person-years, we identified only 40 cases of . he β€�number needed to harmβ€� for 1 year's therapy with  compared with  in this study is around 600. hat said, the  is a country with a relatively low prevalence of . uch a differential risk would probably have greater implications in countries with higher background prevalence. econd, the lower rate with  compared with the other anti- drugs does not mean that there is a negligible risk with this drug. lthough relatively safer than the monoclonal antibodies, clinicians should be aware that  still confers an increased risk. hird, the high prevalence of disseminated  should remind clinicians that  may present atypically in patients treated with anti- therapy. astly, nearly half of the disseminated  cases in patients most recently treated with  occurred after treatment had been stopped, with 13 of the total cases being diagnosed after stopping treatment (6/13 >3 months after stopping). his should remind clinicians to remain vigilant for  even after discontinuing anti- therapy.Discussion
We have confirmed that the monoclonal antibodies INF and ADA are associated with a three- to fourfold higher rate of TB compared with ETA. Although no direct comparison with the DMARD cohort was possible, the expected number of cases (n=10) in the DMARD cohort based on the rate seen in the anti-TNF cohort versus the observed (n=0) suggests that anti-TNF therapy confers a significant risk in patients with active RA. The combined strengths of the large size of the study with the accurate capture of time-dependent drug use and serious adverse event data enabled a robust direct comparison of the rates of TB between the three anti-TNF drugs.
Before concluding that these estimated relative risks represent a true differential risk between the drugs, we should explore alternative explanations. ADA was licensed later, and thus patients receiving ADA may have been more likely to have already received other anti-TNF drugs. Some risk of TB may be carried over from the previous drug, and sequential drug use may have a multiplicative risk. However, the sensitivity analysis censoring follow-up at switching did not change the results. Other factors that may influence the drug-specific rates include calendar year of drug start in parallel with the increasing background UK population rate of TB (12.3 to 14.7 events/100 000 person-years from 2001 to 200520) and increasing awareness of, and changing UK guidelines for, TB screening.21 This was addressed by adjusting all analyses for calendar year of recruitment. Nonetheless, there may be some residual confounding.
It has been suggested that there may be a time-varying risk of TB with anti-TNF therapy, with a higher early increased risk for INF than for ETA.5 Different average durations of follow-up by drug may influence our rate estimates if the risk of TB is nonlinear. However, limiting analysis to the first year of follow-up would result in too few cases to allow meaningful comparison between the drugs.
The early belief that the risk of TB was greater for INF-treated than for ETA-treated patients may have led to a selection bias, where clinicians preferentially prescribed ETA to patients at higher risk of TB. Indeed, proportionally more patients treated with ETA had prior TB, supporting this hypothesis. Assuming no effect of anti-TNF therapy, we might thus expect a higher rate of TB in ETA-treated patients. Our results show the opposite, meaning such a treatment bias does not account for our findings.
Our study did not capture data on all the known risk factors for TB. We did not have data on nutritional status, substance misuse, living environment (eg, residential care), contact with TB, vitamin D deficiency or immunodeficiency states such as HIV.[22] However, it is unlikely that these factors were more prevalent in the monoclonal antibody-treated patients than in the ETA cohort.
Comparing our results with the published literature, we found that there are few studies attempting to examine the question of drug-specific risk. Limitations of prior studies include imprecise estimates of rates in spontaneous pharmacovigilance studies, owing to under-reporting of cases and an unknown denominator4 5 and low numbers of events in observational studies.23 24 The French RATIO study recently attempted to examine drug-specific risk by calculating event β€�ratesβ€� from spontaneously reported cases of TB and estimates of national anti-TNF drug use across all indications.25 Our findings support the original suggestion that the rate of TB may be higher in INF-treated than in ETA-treated patients,3 26 although to a lesser extent than the French study.25 Our finding that TB rates are highest in patients treated with ADA is supported by a high rate of TB in the ADA open-label extension study.12 The possible mechanisms underlying this differential risk of TB have been elegantly reviewed elsewhere.27
Active TB was diagnosed only in patients treated with anti-TNF therapy. If patients in the DMARD cohort had an equal risk to those in the anti-TNF cohort, we would have expected to see 10 TB cases in the DMARD cohort. The magnitude of difference between the observed and expected cases strongly suggests that anti-TNF therapy is associated with significant risk of TB above and beyond the risk conferred by RA alone. The indirect standardisation data also support an increased risk for ETA, where the expected number of cases in the DMARD cohort would have been 3.1. This finding suggests that, although the rates of TB are higher in patients treated with the monoclonal antibodies, patients treated with ETA are not without risk. The average annual incidence of TB for the period of the study in the UK general population was 13.2 events/ 100 000 person-years.20 The anti-TNF rate was therefore eight times higher than in the UK general population. The magnitude of increased risk is higher than the estimated fourfold increased risk conferred by RA in the prebiologic era from non-UK sources.24 Unfortunately, there are no previously published rates of TB in UK RA populations from the pre-biologic era. Because of widely varying international TB incidence, it is not valid to compare our rates with those in other national RA cohorts. Nonetheless, the magnitude of risk in the anti-TNF cohort compared with the general population fits with prior estimates from other countries.23 28
All TB cases in the analysis were confirmed by a doctor. The β€�gold standardβ€� for diagnosing TB is culture of Mycobacterium tuberculosis bacilli. However, in clinical practice, doctors diagnose and treat TB based on weaker criteria such as the presence of acid fast bacilli, caseating granulomata, suggestive radiological findings, or even clinical suspicion. We categorised our cases as verified or unverified. Our tight classification for verified TB led to the exclusion of 16 cases. Nonetheless, restriction to verified cases generated the same pattern of drug-specific risk.
Prior estimates of the frequency of extrapulmonary TB in patients treated with anti-TNF therapy have ranged from 28% to 75%, with most reporting >50% cases as extrapulmonary. Our study replicates these findings, but in addition shows a greater increased risk of extrapulmonary disease with the monoclonal antibodies, a finding not previously described. Our finding of a significant risk conferred by non-white ethnicity in patients treated with anti-TNF therapy also reflects similar findings in the RATIO study.25
There are a number of clinically important points to take from this analysis. First, although the relative risk of TB is three to four times higher for the monoclonal antibodies than for ETA, the actual number of cases is low. After a total follow-up time of nearly 35 000 person-years, we identified only 40 cases of TB. The β€�number needed to harmβ€� for 1 year's therapy with ADA compared with ETA in this study is around 600. That said, the UK is a country with a relatively low prevalence of TB. Such a differential risk would probably have greater implications in countries with higher background prevalence. Second, the lower rate with ETA compared with the other anti-TNF drugs does not mean that there is a negligible risk with this drug. Although relatively safer than the monoclonal antibodies, clinicians should be aware that ETA still confers an increased risk. Third, the high prevalence of disseminated TB should remind clinicians that TB may present atypically in patients treated with anti-TNF therapy. Lastly, nearly half of the disseminated TB cases in patients most recently treated with ADA occurred after treatment had been stopped, with 13 of the total cases being diagnosed after stopping treatment (6/13 >3 months after stopping). This should remind clinicians to remain vigilant for TB even after discontinuing anti-TNF therapy.
